================================================================================
SECTION 1: WHY LIGHT MODE ANIMATIONS ARE DIFFERENT
================================================================================

1.1 THE PHYSICS PROBLEM: ADDITIVE VS SUBTRACTIVE COLOR
-------------------------------------------------------

Every glow, bloom, and neon effect in modern UI design is built on ADDITIVE
color mixing: you ADD light to pixels to make them brighter. This is why glow
effects look spectacular on dark backgrounds -- a dark pixel (e.g., #0D0D0D)
has enormous headroom before it hits white (#FFFFFF). A purple glow at 40%
opacity on black creates a vivid, visible aura.

On UNJYNX's light background (#F8F5FF), the math reverses:
  - #F8F5FF has R=248, G=245, B=255 -- already near maximum brightness
  - Adding a purple glow (#6B21A8 at 40% opacity) barely shifts the pixel:
    Result: rgba(248+27, 245+8, 255+0) = clamped at (255,253,255) -- invisible
  - A gold glow (#B8860B at 30% opacity) similarly vanishes into the pale bg

The mathematical explanation:
  - Additive blend: result = base + (glow * opacity)
  - When base ~= 255 in all channels, result ~= 255 regardless of glow color
  - Bloom effects use Gaussian blur on bright pixels, then ADD the blur back
  - On white, the bright-pixel extraction threshold has nothing to extract
  - Without HDR color space (values > 1.0), bloom is physically impossible on white

Reference: LearnOpenGL Bloom documentation confirms that without HDR rendering,
setting brightness threshold below 1.0 on bright backgrounds causes the glow
to become too dominant or completely invisible. Godot Engine Issue #19361
documents this exact problem with additive bloom blending on light scenes.

1.2 WHAT FAILS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
------------------------------------

EFFECT                  | DARK BG RESULT       | LIGHT BG RESULT
------------------------|----------------------|---------------------------
Outer glow (box-shadow  | Vivid halo           | Invisible or dirty smudge
  with bright color)    |                      |
Neon text-shadow        | Electric, sharp      | Washed out, gray cast
Bloom/HDR bloom         | Cinematic emphasis   | Nonexistent
Particle opacity 60%+   | Dramatic, immersive  | Heavy, cluttered
Bright confetti         | Pops against dark    | Bleached, low contrast
White shimmer highlight | Elegant sweep        | Invisible (white-on-white)
Additive blend particles| Glowing fireflies    | Ghost artifacts

1.3 WHAT WORKS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS (THE UNJYNX TOOLKIT)
---------------------------------------------------------

Instead of additive/glow techniques, light mode uses SUBTRACTIVE emphasis:

TECHNIQUE             | HOW IT WORKS                      | UNJYNX APPLICATION
----------------------|-----------------------------------|------------------------------------
Shadow Pulse          | Animated box-shadow with deeper   | Gold accent shadow pulses on
                      | color, expanding spread radius    | completion: 0 4px 16px #B8860B40
Shadow Deepen         | Shadow intensifies on state       | Card press: shadow deepens from
                      | change (not glow outward)         | 2px to 8px blur, #1A053320
Color Wash            | Fill area with tinted background  | Hover: lavender wash #EDE5F7
                      | color instead of outer glow       | Active: gold wash #FFF8E1
Border Thicken        | Stroke width animates wider       | Progress ring: 3px -> 6px on done
Color Shift           | Hue/saturation transition         | Purple text shifts to gold on tap
Elevation Change      | Shadow + translateY combined      | Card lifts -2px with deeper shadow
Opacity Darken        | Element gets MORE opaque/darker   | Text: #1A0533 at 60% -> 100%
Scale + Shadow combo  | Subtle scale with coordinated     | Button press: scale(0.97) + shadow
                      | shadow reduction                  | shrinks proportionally

1.4 THE LIGHT MODE DESIGN PHILOSOPHY
-------------------------------------

Dark mode = immersive, dramatic, cinematic (entertainment, creativity)
Light mode = clean, calm, professional, focused (productivity, business)

For UNJYNX (a productivity app), light mode is the PRIMARY mode for most
users during working hours. This means:
  - Animations should be 20-30% SHORTER in duration than dark mode equivalents
  - Particle counts should be 30% of dark mode
  - Movement amplitude should be 50% of dark mode
  - Color saturation should be HIGHER (deeper tints, not lighter pastels)
  - Emphasis comes from CONTRAST and SHADOW, not from LIGHT and GLOW

Real-world validation: Todoist, TickTick, and Things 3 all use minimal
animation in light mode. Apple Reminders uses shadow/elevation changes rather
than glow effects. Google Tasks uses color fills (not glows) for completion.

Gartner predicts that by end of 2025, 75% of customer-facing applications will
incorporate micro-interactions as standard UI/UX practice. The ideal duration
for micro-interactions is between 200 and 500 milliseconds -- long enough to be
noticed, yet short enough to maintain flow. Thoughtful motion reduces user error,
improves task completion rates by 15%, and decreases user confusion and support
requests by 18%.

Sources:
