================================================================================
SECTION 3: LOADING & SKELETON STATES (LIGHT MODE)
================================================================================

3.1 SHIMMER LOADING EFFECT (LIGHT MODE SPECIFIC)
--------------------------------------------------

Standard shimmer (gray-on-gray) looks WRONG on UNJYNX's purple-tinted bg.
The shimmer must match the brand's lavender palette.

UNJYNX Light Mode Shimmer Configuration:
  - Base color: #F0EAF5 (slightly darker than #F8F5FF bg -- creates shape)
  - Highlight color: #F8F5FF (matches background -- the "shine" band)
  - Shimmer direction: left-to-right (LTR for LTR languages)
  - Duration: 1500ms per sweep
  - Gradient stops: 0.0 (#F0EAF5), 0.4 (#F0EAF5), 0.5 (#F8F5FF), 0.6 (#F0EAF5), 1.0 (#F0EAF5)
  - Gradient width: 40% of container width (narrow band = more elegant)

WHY NOT standard gray shimmer:
  - #E0E0E0 base on #F8F5FF creates a cold, clinical look
  - #F0EAF5 base maintains the warm purple brand feel
  - Users subconsciously associate the shimmer color with the brand
  - Facebook created the shimmer loading pattern to indicate status;
    UNJYNX extends it with brand-colored shimmers for cohesion

Flutter Implementation (Skeletonizer package):
  - Skeletonizer v2.x supports custom PaintingEffect
  - Configure: ShimmerEffect(
      baseColor: Color(0xFFF0EAF5),
      highlightColor: Color(0xFFF8F5FF),
      duration: Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
    )
  - Alternative: shimmer_ai package with baseColor: Colors.deepPurple.shade50
    (zero-configuration shimmer with one line of code)

The Skeletonizer package (pub.dev/packages/skeletonizer) reduces existing
layouts into skeletons and applies painting effects automatically. The
flutter_shimmer package also offers a built-in PurplishMode (isPurplishMode: true)
which provides purple-tinted shimmer out of the box -- almost exactly matching
UNJYNX's brand palette.

For light themes, SkeletonizerPlus automatically uses Colors.grey[300] as base
and Colors.grey[100] as highlight. We override these with our lavender values.

3.2 PULL-TO-REFRESH ANIMATION
-------------------------------

Light mode pull-to-refresh should be CLEANER than dark mode:

  - Phase 1 (Pull 0-60px): UNJYNX logo outline appears, scales 0.0 -> 1.0
    - Logo color: #6B21A8 (deep purple, visible on light bg)
    - NO shimmer during pull -- just clean scale animation
  - Phase 2 (Pull 60px+, threshold): Logo fills with gold (#B8860B)
    - Rotation begins: 0 -> 360 degrees, 800ms per revolution
    - Easing: Curves.linear (constant speed = "working" feel)
  - Phase 3 (Loading): Logo continues rotating
    - Small text "Syncing..." in #1A053380 appears below
  - Phase 4 (Complete): Logo scale pulses 1.0 -> 1.1 -> 1.0
    - Gold fill transitions to green checkmark briefly (200ms)
    - Then fades out with slide-up: translateY(-20px) + opacity 0

Why NOT a spinner:
  - Branded refresh > generic spinner for premium feel
  - Purple + gold logo animation reinforces brand with every refresh
  - Estimated ~30 refreshes/day per user = 30 brand impressions

3.3 CONTENT LOADING TRANSITIONS
---------------------------------

When real content replaces skeletons:

  - Skeleton fades out: opacity 1.0 -> 0.0, 200ms
  - Real content fades in: opacity 0.0 -> 1.0, 200ms, 50ms delay per item
  - Stagger: each list item appears 50ms after the previous
  - This creates a "cascade" effect that feels fast and intentional
  - NO slide-in from bottom (adds unnecessary motion on light mode)
  - Curve: Curves.easeOut (quick start, gentle settle)

3.4 EMPTY STATE ANIMATIONS
----------------------------

When a list has no items (empty inbox, completed all tasks):

  - Use Lottie animation (fire-and-forget, no interaction needed)
  - Colors: deep purple (#6B21A8) lines, gold (#B8860B) accents
  - NOT pastel colors (they disappear on #F8F5FF)
  - Subtle loop: character/illustration has idle breathing or floating motion
  - Loop duration: 3000ms (slow, calm, matches productivity context)
  - Size: max 200x200px (don't dominate the screen)

Sources:
- Flutter Shimmer Cookbook: https://docs.flutter.dev/cookbook/effects/shimmer-loading
- Skeletonizer Package: https://pub.dev/packages/skeletonizer
- Shimmer AI Package: https://pub.dev/packages/shimmer_ai
- flutter_shimmer PurplishMode: https://github.com/skaran921/flutter_shimmer
- Skeletonizer Plus Package: https://pub.dev/packages/skeletonizer_plus
- LogRocket Shimmer Flutter: https://blog.logrocket.com/implement-shimmer-effect-flutter/


================================================================================
SECTION 4: PARTICLE SYSTEMS ON LIGHT BACKGROUNDS
================================================================================

4.1 THE LIGHT MODE PARTICLE RULES
-----------------------------------

Rule 1: 30% PARTICLE COUNT of dark mode
  Dark mode: 100 ambient particles -> Light mode: 30 particles
  Reason: Light backgrounds feel cluttered faster. Fewer particles = calmer.

Rule 2: 20-30% LESS OPACITY per particle
  Dark mode particle: opacity 0.4-0.6 -> Light mode: opacity 0.15-0.35
  Reason: Dark particles on light bg have inherently more contrast than
  light particles on dark bg. Less opacity compensates.

Rule 3: DEEPER TINT (saturated, not pastel)
  Dark mode: light lavender #C4B5FD -> Light mode: deep violet #6B21A8
  Reason: Pastel on near-white = invisible. Deep colors maintain visibility.

Rule 4: 50% MOVEMENT AMPLITUDE
  Dark mode: 20px drift range -> Light mode: 10px drift range
  Reason: Light mode = work mode = calm. Excessive particle motion = distraction.

Rule 5: NO ADDITIVE BLENDING
  Dark mode: BlendMode.plus (additive) -> Light mode: BlendMode.srcOver (normal)
  Reason: Additive blending on white creates artifacts, not beauty.

4.2 SPECIFIC PARTICLE TYPES ADAPTED FOR LIGHT
-----------------------------------------------

PRODUCTIVITY STATE PARTICLES (ambient while working):
  Dark: Floating light-purple dots, opacity 0.3, 80 particles
  Light: Floating deep-purple dots, opacity 0.12, 25 particles
         Color: #6B21A840 -> #6B21A820 (gradient fade)
         Size: 2-4px (slightly smaller than dark mode 3-6px)
         Speed: 0.3px/frame drift (half of dark mode 0.6px/frame)
         Blur: 1px Gaussian (soft, not sharp)

CELEBRATION PARTICLES (task/project completion confetti):
  Dark: Bright multi-color, 100 particles, opacity 0.7-1.0
  Light: Deep-tinted multi-color, 40-60 particles, opacity 0.5-0.8
         Colors: #B8860B, #6B21A8, #1A0533, #D4763B, #9333EA
         NO white or yellow particles (invisible on light bg)
         NO pastel pink/blue (too soft, low contrast)
         Size: 4-8px rectangles/circles (same as dark -- need visibility)

AMBIENT SOUND PARTICLES (soundscape visualization):
  Rain:  Dark: light blue dots falling | Light: #4B6B8A dots, opacity 0.20
  Forest: Dark: green floating leaves | Light: #2D5A27 leaves, opacity 0.15
  Cafe:  Dark: warm orange wisps | Light: #8B6914 wisps, opacity 0.12
  Ocean: Dark: teal flowing waves | Light: #1A6B7A waves, opacity 0.18
  Fire:  Dark: bright orange embers | Light: #B8860B embers, opacity 0.25

SEASONAL PARTICLES (see Section 10 for full details):
  Snow:   #C8C0D0 flakes (NOT white -- visible on #F8F5FF)
  Sakura: #D4547A petals (deeper pink, not pastel)
  Autumn: #8B5E3C, #B8860B leaves (warm, saturated)
  Diwali: #D4763B, #B8860B sparks (warm gold/orange -- natural on light)

4.3 FLUTTER CUSTOMPAINTER IMPLEMENTATION
-----------------------------------------

For custom particle systems on light backgrounds, CustomPainter is the
recommended approach. The paint() method iterates over all particles and
queries their progress values. AnimationController drives the animation loop.

Key implementation notes for light mode:
  - Use canvas.drawCircle with Paint()..color = particleColor.withOpacity(computed)
  - Set Paint()..blendMode = BlendMode.srcOver (NOT BlendMode.plus)
  - Apply Paint()..maskFilter = MaskFilter.blur(BlurStyle.normal, 1.0) for softness
  - Use shouldRepaint() returning true only when particles have moved
  - Particle pool pattern: pre-allocate List<Particle> to avoid GC pressure
  - Target: 60fps with <30 particles is trivially achievable on modern devices

Custom Painters offload complex rendering tasks to the GPU by strategically
using them, enhancing performance and resulting in smoother animations.
Widgets are composited together using a minimum number of Canvases for
performance reasons. The shouldRepaint method tells Flutter whether the canvas
needs to be redrawn when the widget rebuilds -- return false when nothing
has changed to save resources.

Performance benchmarks (approximate):
  - 30 particles with blur: ~0.5ms paint time on mid-range device
  - 100 particles with blur: ~1.5ms paint time (still fine for 60fps budget of 16ms)
  - 200+ particles: consider using flutter_gpu or Rive for GPU-accelerated rendering

4.4 PARTICLE INTERACTIVITY ON LIGHT MODE
------------------------------------------

Unlike dark mode where particles can be dramatic and interactive (cursor
magnetism, touch ripples), light mode particles should be:
  - NON-INTERACTIVE by default (ambient, background decoration)
  - Exception: celebration confetti has physics (gravity, collision)
  - Exception: sound visualization particles respond to audio levels
  - Touch interaction only in dedicated views (ambient sound picker)
  - Never in task list or productivity views (distraction)

Sources:
- particles.js Library: https://vincentgarreau.com/particles.js/
- tsParticles Library: https://particles.js.org/
- Flutter CustomPainter Particle Guide: https://medium.com/easy-flutter/flutter-magic-build-your-own-particle-system-and-look-like-a-wizard-b1fa55b75c85
- CustomPainter Performance: https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/boost-performance-interactivity-custom-painters-qudus-fatungase
- Codemagic CustomPaint Guide: https://blog.codemagic.io/flutter-custom-painter/


================================================================================
SECTION 5: TRANSITION ANIMATIONS
================================================================================

5.1 SCREEN-TO-SCREEN TRANSITIONS
----------------------------------

Light mode transitions should feel FAST and CLEAN, not dramatic:

PUSH TRANSITION (navigating deeper):
  - Incoming screen: slideIn from right, 300ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Outgoing screen: slideOut to left at 30% speed (parallax depth)
  - Background: static #F8F5FF (no color transitions)
  - DO NOT add fade -- pure slide is cleaner on light backgrounds

POP TRANSITION (going back):
  - Reverse of push: incoming from left, outgoing to right
  - Duration: 250ms (slightly faster than push -- feels responsive)

MODAL PRESENTATION (bottom sheet, dialogs):
  - Bottom sheet: slides up with spring physics
    - Spring: mass 1.0, stiffness 500, damping 30 (slightly bouncy)
    - Background scrim: rgba(26,5,51,0.25) -- purple-tinted, not plain black
    - Scrim fade: 200ms, Curves.easeOut
    - Flutter's showModalBottomSheet supports sheetAnimationStyle parameter
      to override entrance and exit animation duration/curve
    - spring_bottom_sheet package provides custom spring physics with
      configurable mass, stiffness, and damping parameters
  - Dialog: scale(0.95) -> scale(1.0) + opacity 0 -> 1, 200ms
    - Background scrim: same purple-tinted scrim

TAB SWITCH:
  - Crossfade between tab contents: 150ms, Curves.easeInOut
  - Tab indicator: animated position with Curves.easeOutCubic, 200ms
  - Tab indicator color: #B8860B (gold, matches brand accent)

5.2 HERO TRANSITIONS
----------------------

Flutter's Hero widget creates shared element transitions between screens.
The Hero widget implements a "flying" animation from source to destination
route. During flight, the hero widget appears above both routes, creating
visually pleasing continuity.

For UNJYNX light mode:

  - Task card -> Task detail: card expands with Hero tag
  - Profile avatar -> Profile screen: circular Hero transition
  - Project icon -> Project detail: icon flies to header position

Light mode specific adjustments:
  - Hero flight should NOT have a shadow trail (looks dirty on light bg)
  - Instead, use a subtle elevation: during flight, shadow increases
    from 2px to 8px blur, then settles back to 4px on destination
  - The Hero widget's flightShuttleBuilder can customize the in-flight widget:
    add a DecoratedBox with increasing BoxShadow during the transition
  - Hero also supports custom shape transforms via rectTween: widgets can
    morph from circular to rectangular during flight

5.3 GHOST MODE ENTRY TRANSITION (THE DRAMATIC ONE)
----------------------------------------------------

Ghost Mode is the ONE transition where we break all light-mode rules:

The concept: User activates Ghost Mode (deep focus) and the entire UI
transforms from light to dark with a dramatic reveal.

PHASE 1: Activation (0-100ms)
  - Haptic: UIImpactFeedbackGenerator.heavy
  - Ghost Mode button pulses once with gold wash

PHASE 2: The Crossfade (100-800ms)
  - Start: #F8F5FF (Purple Mist) across entire screen
  - A CIRCULAR REVEAL expands from the Ghost Mode button position
  - Inside the circle: deep purple #1A0533 with all dark-mode styling
  - Outside the circle: still #F8F5FF light mode
  - Circle expands to cover full screen using clip-path animation
  - Easing: Curves.easeInOutCubic (smooth acceleration/deceleration)

PHASE 3: Dark Mode Settle (800-1200ms)
  - All elements have completed their color transitions
  - Ambient particles activate (dark mode count: 80-100)
  - Stars/subtle glow effects appear (only possible now on dark bg)
  - Sound: optional subtle "whoosh" or low hum

PHASE 4: Exit (reverse)
  - Circle contracts from edges to center
  - Light mode elements restore from center outward
  - Particles fade out during contraction
  - Total exit: 600ms (faster than entry -- returning to work)

This is based on the circular reveal animation technique documented in
Android theme switching: capture a snapshot of the current state, overlay it,
and animate a clip-path from small circle to full screen. The strategy
involves gracefully overlaying the snapshot and smoothly transitioning the
system's mode.

5.4 THEME SWITCHING ANIMATION (SETTINGS)
------------------------------------------

For the manual light/dark toggle in Settings (not Ghost Mode):

  - Use View Transitions API concepts adapted for Flutter
  - Capture a "screenshot" of current state using RepaintBoundary
  - Overlay the screenshot on top of the new theme
  - Crossfade the overlay: opacity 1.0 -> 0.0, 400ms
  - This prevents the ugly flash of unstyled theme change
  - Alternative: circular ripple from the toggle switch position

  Multiple animation variants are available: circle, blur, polygon, and
  custom masks with flexible positioning. Animations can start from center,
  corners, or edges.

5.5 CARD EXPANSION/COLLAPSE
------------------------------

Task cards that expand to show subtasks/details:

  - Expand: height animates open, 300ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Content fades in with 100ms delay after height animation starts
  - Shadow deepens during expansion: 2px blur -> 6px blur
  - Collapse: reverse, 250ms (slightly faster)
  - Chevron icon rotates 0 -> 180 degrees synchronously

5.6 LIST ITEM STAGGER ANIMATIONS
----------------------------------

When a list first loads (not shimmer -> content, but initial render):

  - Each item slides in from 20px right + fades from opacity 0
  - Stagger delay: 50ms per item (max 10 items animated, rest appear instantly)
  - Duration per item: 300ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - This uses flutter_staggered_animations package:
    AnimationConfiguration.staggeredList(
      position: index,
      duration: Duration(milliseconds: 300),
      child: SlideAnimation(
        horizontalOffset: 20.0,  // subtle, not dramatic
        child: FadeInAnimation(child: listItem),
      ),
    )

Sources:
- Flutter Hero Animations: https://docs.flutter.dev/ui/animations/hero-animations
- Flutter Staggered Animations: https://docs.flutter.dev/ui/animations/staggered-animations
- Vibe Studio Page Transitions: https://vibe-studio.ai/insights/animating-page-transitions-in-flutter-for-premium-ux
- Theme Switching Circular Reveal: https://medium.com/@ankit_kr/build-a-beautiful-dark-mode-toggle-with-circular-reveal-animation-in-android-d55feb5cfed5
- View Transitions Approach: https://medium.com/@AkashHamirwasia/full-page-theme-toggle-animation-with-view-transitions-api-43db0beed341
- spring_bottom_sheet: https://pub.dev/packages/spring_bottom_sheet
- Blup Advanced Flutter Transitions: https://www.blup.in/blog/advanced-flutter-animation-techniques-hero-animations-route-transitions


================================================================================
SECTION 6: HOVER/PRESS/FOCUS STATES (LIGHT MODE)
================================================================================

6.1 PRESS STATES (MOBILE-PRIMARY)
-----------------------------------

Since UNJYNX is mobile-first, press states replace hover states. On mobile,
the ripple effect replaces hover, providing visual feedback when users tap a
button and assuring them their finger hit the target accurately.

PRIMARY BUTTON PRESS:
  - Rest: bg #6B21A8, text #FFFFFF, shadow 0 2px 4px rgba(26,5,51,0.15)
  - Pressed: scale(0.97), bg #5B1898 (slightly darker), shadow 0 1px 2px rgba(26,5,51,0.1)
  - Release: spring back to scale(1.0), 150ms, Curves.easeOutBack
  - Ripple: Material InkWell with color rgba(255,255,255,0.2) (light ripple on dark button)
  - Haptic: HapticFeedback.lightImpact
  - Timing: animate state transitions quickly at 100-300ms

SECONDARY BUTTON PRESS:
  - Rest: bg transparent, border 1.5px #6B21A8, text #6B21A8
  - Pressed: bg rgba(107,33,168,0.08) (lavender wash), scale(0.97)
  - Release: bg fades back to transparent, 150ms
  - Ripple: InkWell with color rgba(107,33,168,0.1) (purple ripple)

GHOST BUTTON (text-only):
  - Rest: no bg, text #6B21A8
  - Pressed: bg rgba(107,33,168,0.06), scale(0.98)
  - The wash fill is critical on light mode -- opacity changes alone
    are too subtle to perceive on #F8F5FF

ICON BUTTON PRESS:
  - Rest: icon #1A053380 (60% opacity midnight purple)
  - Pressed: icon #1A0533 (100% opacity) + bg circle rgba(107,33,168,0.08)
  - The bg circle provides the "target hit" feedback that hover provides on desktop

DANGER BUTTON (delete, remove):
  - Rest: bg #DC2626, text #FFFFFF
  - Pressed: scale(0.97), bg #B91C1C (darker red)
  - Haptic: HapticFeedback.mediumImpact (stronger = "are you sure?")

Design research shows: A button design can include an onclick animation where
the button briefly shrinks and then expands back to its original size when
clicked, providing tactile feedback and simulating a physical press. Hover
animations should feel light and purposeful -- over-the-top motion slows users
down and reduces perceived quality.

6.2 HOVER STATES (TABLET/DESKTOP)
-----------------------------------

For iPad and desktop web versions:

CARD HOVER:
  - Rest: bg #FFFFFF, shadow 0 1px 3px rgba(26,5,51,0.08)
  - Hover: bg #FFFFFF, shadow 0 4px 12px rgba(26,5,51,0.12), translateY(-1px)
  - Transition: 150ms ease-out
  - DO NOT change bg to lavender on hover (save wash for active/focus)

LIST ITEM HOVER:
  - Rest: bg transparent
  - Hover: bg #F0EAF5 (lavender wash -- NOT opacity change)
  - Transition: 100ms ease-in-out
  - This follows the principle: on light backgrounds, use FILL changes
    not OPACITY changes for hover feedback

LINK HOVER:
  - Rest: text #6B21A8, no underline
  - Hover: text #5B1898 (darker), underline appears
  - Transition: color 100ms, underline slides in from left 200ms

6.3 FOCUS STATES (KEYBOARD/ACCESSIBILITY)
-------------------------------------------

Focus rings are CRITICAL for accessibility and must be visible on light bg:

  - Focus ring: 2px solid #6B21A8 with 4px offset from element
  - Offset achieved with outline-offset (CSS) or custom painter (Flutter)
  - Ring color MUST contrast against both the element AND the #F8F5FF bg
  - #6B21A8 on #F8F5FF = contrast ratio 7.2:1 (exceeds WCAG AAA)
  - Animation: ring fades in 100ms (not instant -- too jarring)

6.4 ACTIVE/SELECTED STATES
-----------------------------

  - Selected tab: gold wash #FFF8E1 bg + #B8860B text + 2px bottom border
  - Selected list item: lavender wash #EDE5F7 bg + #1A0533 text (full opacity)
  - Active toggle: bg transitions from #D1C4E9 to #6B21A8, 200ms
  - Disabled state: 40% opacity (not lower -- must remain readable on light)
    Contrast check: #1A0533 at 40% on #F8F5FF = ~4.2:1 (meets WCAG AA)

6.5 MULTI-SENSORY PAIRING
---------------------------

Every state change pairs visual feedback with haptic feedback.
A sharp, quick visual animation pairs well with a crisp light haptic tap
and a short, high-pitched sound. Haptic feedback and audio feedback must be
closely synchronized since they often share the same predictable patterns.

  ACTION          | VISUAL                    | HAPTIC              | AUDIO
  ----------------|---------------------------|---------------------|------------------
  Button press    | Scale(0.97) + color shift | lightImpact         | None
  Task complete   | Gold fill + strikethrough | lightImpact         | Optional soft tick
  Delete swipe    | Red reveal + scale        | mediumImpact        | None
  Error           | Red shake (3x, 4px)       | notificationError   | Optional buzz
  Success         | Green flash + check       | notificationSuccess | Optional chime
  Pull-to-refresh | Logo rotation             | selectionClick      | None

Key principle: haptic and visual must be SYNCHRONOUS -- even 50ms desync
feels broken. Sharp visual animation pairs with crisp haptic tap.
Slow animations pair with no haptic (haptic on a 500ms animation feels random).

Transient haptic events are brief experiences like one-tap coordination,
while continuous events are drawn-out and recurring vibrations. Patterns
differentiate actions: a single buzz for success, a triple buzz for error.

Be careful not to overuse haptics in UX. Too much haptic feedback makes the
UI more complex and risks annoying users. For blind or low-vision users,
haptics provide vital non-visual confirmation, complementing screen readers.

Sources:
- Mockplus Button State Design: https://www.mockplus.com/blog/post/button-state-design
- DesignRush Button States 2026: https://www.designrush.com/best-designs/websites/trends/button-states
- LogRocket Button States Tutorial: https://blog.logrocket.com/ux-design/designing-button-states/
- UX Movement Mobile Hover: https://uxmovement.com/mobile/the-hover-effect-for-mobile-buttons/
- Saropa Haptics Guide 2025: https://saropa-contacts.medium.com/2025-guide-to-haptics-enhancing-mobile-ux-with-tactile-feedback-676dd5937774
- Android Haptics UX Design: https://source.android.com/docs/core/interaction/haptics/haptics-ux-design
- Wings Design Multi-Sensory UX: https://wings.design/multi-sensory-ux-integrating-haptics-sound-and-visual-cues-to-enhance-user-interaction/
- Boreas Haptic UX Guidelines: https://pages.boreas.ca/blog/piezo-haptics/guidelines-of-haptic-ux-design


================================================================================
SECTION 7: SCROLL & GESTURE ANIMATIONS
================================================================================

7.1 PARALLAX ON SCROLL
------------------------

UNJYNX uses parallax sparingly in light mode (it's a productivity app, not
a marketing page). Parallax scrolling is a technique where background and
foreground content scroll at different speeds, creating a sense of depth.

PROJECT HEADER PARALLAX:
  - Background image/gradient scrolls at 0.3x speed (foreground at 1.0x)
  - Header gradient: #EDE5F7 -> #F8F5FF (lavender to mist)
  - Speed factor 0.3 feels natural without causing motion sickness
    (> 0.7 can induce vestibular discomfort per accessibility research)
  - Transforms run on the compositor thread for smooth 60fps
  - Adding willChange: transform tells browsers to optimize these elements

CALENDAR VIEW PARALLAX:
  - Month header stays fixed, dates scroll beneath
  - Header has 4px bottom shadow that INTENSIFIES as content scrolls under
  - Shadow transitions: 0 1px 2px rgba(26,5,51,0.05) -> 0 4px 8px rgba(26,5,51,0.12)

Flutter implementation uses ScrollController.offset to drive parallax:
  Transform.translate(
    offset: Offset(0, scrollOffset * 0.3),
    child: headerBackground,
  )

7.2 HEADER COLLAPSE/EXPAND WITH BLUR
--------------------------------------

SliverAppBar with expandedHeight for task list views:

EXPANDED STATE (scroll position 0):
  - Full height: 200px
  - Shows: greeting, date, quick stats
  - Background: solid #F8F5FF (no blur needed)
  - Stats text: #1A0533 at 80% opacity

COLLAPSING (scroll 0 -> 120px):
  - Height shrinks: 200px -> 80px
  - Greeting text fades out (opacity 1.0 -> 0.0 over first 60px of scroll)
  - Stats text fades out next (opacity 1.0 -> 0.0 over scroll 40-100px)
  - Title text scales: fontSize 28 -> 20
  - Background blur: NO BLUR on light mode (blur on white = gray wash = ugly)
    Instead: a 1px bottom border appears at rgba(26,5,51,0.08)

COLLAPSED STATE (scroll > 120px):
  - Height: 80px (standard app bar)
  - Shows: title only, with action buttons
  - Bottom border: solid 1px rgba(26,5,51,0.08)
  - Elevation: 0 (flat on light mode -- Material 3 style)

Note: A sticky navigation that shrinks when scrolling down and expands when
scrolling back up is a small but fun interaction that can improve UX. Light
mode benefits more from border separators than shadow elevation.

7.3 SWIPE ACTION REVEALS
--------------------------

Swipe-to-reveal for task list items. iOS-style swipe interfaces reveal
contextual actions when users swipe items left or right, providing a
space-efficient alternative to permanent action visibility.

RIGHT SWIPE (leading -- positive actions):
  - Reveals: Complete button
  - Background: #16A34A (deep green -- visible on light, not pastel)
  - Icon: white checkmark, scales in from 0.5 -> 1.0
  - Threshold: 80px to trigger, with rubber-band resistance past 120px

LEFT SWIPE (trailing -- destructive/contextual):
  - Reveals: Delete, Snooze buttons
  - Delete bg: #DC2626 (deep red -- strong contrast on light)
  - Snooze bg: #B8860B (gold -- brand accent)
  - Icons: white, scale animation matching swipe distance
  - Threshold: 80px for first action, 160px for full delete

Following iOS Human Interface Guidelines: trailing (right-to-left gesture) is
for destructive or context-ending actions (Delete, Archive), while leading
(left-to-right) is for contextual shortcuts (Pin, Read, Mark as Favourite).

Both swipes include:
  - Subtle shadow on the swiping card edge (the card appears to lift)
  - Content behind scales from 0.8 -> 1.0 as it reveals
  - Undo snackbar appears for 5 seconds after destructive actions
  - Gmail-style: immediate feedback after swipe with undo option

7.4 OVERSCROLL BOUNCE
-----------------------

  - iOS default: rubber-band bounce (ClampingScrollPhysics on Android)
  - UNJYNX customization: overscroll area shows subtle lavender gradient
    that intensifies with pull distance
  - At max overscroll (40px): bg shifts from #F8F5FF to #EDE5F7
  - This branded overscroll subtly reinforces the purple theme
  - Uses BouncingScrollPhysics (iOS-style) on both platforms for consistency

7.5 DRAG-TO-REORDER
---------------------

When reordering tasks in a list:

  - Long press (500ms) triggers: card lifts with shadow increase
    Shadow: 0 2px 4px -> 0 8px 24px rgba(26,5,51,0.15)
  - Card scales to 1.03 (slight growth = "picked up")
  - Haptic: HapticFeedback.mediumImpact on pickup
  - Other items animate out of the way: 200ms translateY
  - Drop: card settles with spring physics, shadow returns to rest
  - Haptic: HapticFeedback.lightImpact on drop
  - Light mode specific: card gets a 1px #6B21A840 border during drag
    (provides definition that shadow alone doesn't give on light bg)

Sources:
- Flutter Parallax Scrolling: https://docs.flutter.dev/cookbook/effects/parallax-scrolling
- Builder.io Parallax Guide 2026: https://www.builder.io/blog/parallax-scrolling-effect
- LogRocket Swipe Design: https://blog.logrocket.com/ux-design/accessible-swipe-contextual-action-triggers/
- NNGroup Swipe Interactions: https://www.nngroup.com/articles/contextual-swipe/
- W3Schools Parallax: https://www.w3schools.com/howto/howto_css_parallax.asp
- Webflow Parallax: https://webflow.com/blog/parallax-scrolling


================================================================================
SECTION 8: DATA VISUALIZATION ANIMATIONS (LIGHT MODE)
================================================================================

8.1 PROGRESS RINGS (LIGHT MODE ADAPTATION)
--------------------------------------------

Progress rings are a core UNJYNX visual (task progress, daily goals, streaks).

LIGHT MODE RING SPECIFICATION:
  - Track (background): #EDE5F7 (lavender -- NOT gray)
  - Fill (progress): #6B21A8 (deep violet) for < 100%
  - Fill (complete): #B8860B (gold) when 100%
  - Track width: 4px
  - Fill width: 4px (SAME as track -- thickens to 6px on completion animation)

ANIMATION:
  - Initial draw: 0% -> current% over 800ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Progress update: old% -> new% over 400ms, Curves.easeInOutCubic
  - Completion (reaching 100%):
    1. Fill color transitions #6B21A8 -> #B8860B (purple to gold), 300ms
    2. Ring THICKENS: 4px -> 6px -> 4px, 400ms (pulse effect)
    3. Shimmer sweeps along the filled ring (gradient highlight)
       Shimmer: traveling highlight of #D4A847 (lighter gold) over #B8860B
       Shimmer duration: 600ms, one sweep
    4. Optional: 3-5 tiny spark particles emit from the 12 o'clock position

WHY thicken instead of glow:
  - Outer glow on a 4px ring on #F8F5FF = invisible
  - Thickening is visible, satisfying, and physically intuitive
  - The shimmer sweep provides the "special" feel that glow would on dark

DAILY GOAL RING (home screen):
  - Larger: 120px diameter
  - Center text: animated counter "7/10" with number counting animation
  - Uses animated_flip_counter package for smooth digit transitions
  - Text color: #1A0533 (full contrast on light bg)
  - Sub-text "tasks today" in #1A053360 (60% opacity)

Animated Gauge and Progress Circle components are fully customizable for
data visualization, allowing customization of color, stroke width, stroke
linecap, and stroke length percentage.

8.2 CHART LINE DRAWING ANIMATION
----------------------------------

Weekly/monthly productivity charts:

LINE CHART:
  - Line color: #6B21A8 (deep purple -- high visibility on light bg)
  - Line width: 2px with rounded caps
  - Draw animation: path reveals left-to-right, 1000ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Area fill below line: gradient from #6B21A820 (top) to #6B21A805 (bottom)
  - Grid lines: #EDE5F7 (lavender, not gray)
  - Axis labels: #1A053360 (60% opacity midnight purple)
  - Data points: 6px circles, #6B21A8 fill, appear with 50ms stagger after line draws

BAR CHART:
  - Bars: #6B21A8 fill, 8px border-radius top corners
  - Draw animation: bars grow from bottom, 600ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Stagger: 50ms between each bar
  - Hover/tap on bar: bar brightens to #7C3AED + tooltip appears
  - Background grid: horizontal lines at #EDE5F7

Animation in data visualization should focus on conveying information and
enhancing understanding of data. Animation for the sake of animation detracts
from this purpose. Subtle animations can indicate loading states or progress
of data queries, providing visual cues and reducing perceived wait times.

8.3 HEATMAP CELL TRANSITIONS
-------------------------------

Activity heatmap (like GitHub contributions):

COLOR SCALE FOR LIGHT MODE:
  Level 0 (no activity):    #F0EAF5 (slightly darker than bg, not gray)
  Level 1 (low):            #D1C4E9
  Level 2 (medium):         #9333EA40 (purple at 25% opacity)
  Level 3 (high):           #6B21A8
  Level 4 (exceptional):    #B8860B (gold -- reward color)

ANIMATION:
  - Cells fade in with 20ms stagger (left-to-right, top-to-bottom)
  - Duration per cell: 200ms, Curves.easeOut
  - On tap: cell scales to 1.5 + tooltip shows date and count
  - The gold level 4 is unique to UNJYNX -- competitors use darkest shade of
    one color; we reward exceptional days with the brand's gold accent

8.4 NUMBER COUNTER ANIMATIONS
-------------------------------

Used in stats, streaks, and dashboard:

  - Package: animated_flip_counter (pub.dev)
  - Digits flip/slide vertically when changing
  - Duration: 400ms per digit change
  - Curve: Curves.easeInOut
  - Text style: fontSize 32, fontWeight 700, color #1A0533
  - For large numbers (1000+): comma separators also animate in
  - You simply pass a value and optional duration and curve, just like any
    other implicit animation widget in Flutter

  Alternative: smooth_counter for simpler counting
  - Counts from old value to new value with interpolation
  - Duration: 600ms for small changes, up to 1200ms for large jumps
  - Simple arguments: pass a number (int or double) and animation performs

  Alternative: animated_digit for scroll number effects
  - Scroll numbers animation widget for any number needing scroll effects

8.5 STREAK FLAME VISUALIZATION
---------------------------------

The streak flame on light backgrounds needs special treatment:

  - Flame gradient: #D4763B (outer) -> #B8860B (middle) -> #FFC107 (inner/tip)
  - These are WARMER, DEEPER tones than the bright orange/yellow used on dark
  - Drop shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(26,5,51,0.12) (purple shadow GROUNDS it on light bg)
  - Without the shadow, the flame "floats" and looks disconnected on white
  - Size increase animation per streak tier: 24px -> 32px -> 40px
  - Idle animation: gentle sway +-3 degrees rotation, 2000ms loop
  - Implemented in Rive for interactive state machine (responds to streak count)

Sources:
- Flourish Animated Charts: https://flourish.studio/blog/animated-charts/
- Flutter Charts Packages: https://fluttergems.dev/plots-visualization/
- animated_flip_counter: https://pub.dev/packages/animated_flip_counter
- smooth_counter: https://pub.dev/packages/smooth_counter
- animated_digit: https://pub.dev/packages/animated_digit
- Duolingo Streak Design: https://blog.duolingo.com/streak-milestone-design-animation/
- Visme Data Visualizations 2026: https://visme.co/blog/best-data-visualizations/


================================================================================
SECTION 9: NOTIFICATION & FEEDBACK ANIMATIONS
================================================================================

9.1 TOAST/SNACKBAR ENTRY ANIMATION
-------------------------------------

Toasts are auto-dismissing status messages used to convey information without
disrupting user workflows. Snackbars are short, temporary notifications that
appear at the bottom of the screen, typically informing users about processes.
The key difference: snackbars include action buttons, toasts do not.

TOAST (informational, auto-dismiss):
  - Entry: slides up from bottom edge, 250ms, Curves.easeOutCubic
  - Background: #1A0533 (dark on light -- inverted for visibility)
  - Text: #FFFFFF
  - Border-radius: 12px
  - Shadow: 0 4px 12px rgba(26,5,51,0.15)
  - Auto-dismiss: 3000ms display, then slides down 200ms
  - Position: 80px from bottom (above FAB and nav bar)

SNACKBAR (actionable, user-dismiss):
  - Same entry animation as toast
  - Action button: #B8860B text (gold on dark snackbar = branded)
  - Dismiss: swipe right or tap action, 200ms slide-right exit
  - Duration: 5000ms default, infinite for critical actions

SUCCESS FEEDBACK:
  - Green-tinted snackbar: bg #16A34A, icon white checkmark
  - Entry includes a brief "bounce" at landing (scaleY 1.0 -> 1.05 -> 1.0)
  - Duration: 2000ms (shorter -- success is quick positive feedback)

ERROR FEEDBACK:
  - Red-tinted snackbar: bg #DC2626, icon white exclamation
  - Entry includes a brief SHAKE: translateX 0 -> 4px -> -4px -> 2px -> 0, 300ms
  - This shake-on-entry immediately communicates "something went wrong"
  - Duration: 5000ms (longer -- user needs time to read error)
  - Haptic: HapticFeedback.notificationError

WARNING FEEDBACK:
  - Gold-tinted snackbar: bg #B8860B, icon white warning triangle
  - No special entry animation beyond standard slide-up
  - Duration: 4000ms

Animation duration for show/hide defaults to 250ms. Higher values create
slower, more deliberate animations. Modern implementations like ToastfierJS
prioritize accessibility compliance with WCAG 2.1 standards and support for
screen readers, and respect "Reduced Motion" user preferences.

9.2 BADGE COUNT INCREMENT
---------------------------

When notification badges update:

  - Badge: 20px circle, bg #DC2626 (red), text #FFFFFF
  - Increment animation: scale(1.0) -> scale(1.3) -> scale(1.0), 200ms
  - The scale bump draws attention without being obnoxious
  - If going from 0 to 1: badge enters with scale(0) -> scale(1.3) -> scale(1.0)
    (spring entrance, 300ms)
  - If going from N to 0: badge exits with scale(1.0) -> scale(0), 200ms
  - Number text: crossfade old -> new during the scale animation

9.3 NOTIFICATION DOT PULSE
-----------------------------

The "unread" dot on nav bar items:

  - Dot: 8px circle, #DC2626 (red) or #B8860B (gold for priority)
  - Pulse animation: scale(1.0) -> scale(1.4) with opacity(0.4) ring
  - The RING is the "pulse" (not the dot itself -- dot stays solid)
  - Ring expands from 8px to 16px, opacity 0.4 -> 0.0, 1200ms loop
  - This creates a subtle "radar ping" effect
  - On light mode, ring color: rgba(220,38,38,0.15) (red with low opacity)
    NOT rgba(220,38,38,0.4) (too heavy on light bg)
  - Pulse repeats 3 times then stops (infinite pulse = annoying)

9.4 AI WHISPER CRYSTAL BALL (LIGHT MODE)
------------------------------------------

The AI Whisper feature uses an orb/crystal ball metaphor:

DARK MODE ORB: Glowing, luminous, ethereal with light emissions
LIGHT MODE ORB: VERY different approach required

LIGHT MODE ORB SPECIFICATION:
  - Base: semi-transparent glass sphere with subtle purple tint
  - Color: rgba(107,33,168,0.08) fill with 1px rgba(107,33,168,0.15) border
  - Inner motion: subtle swirling gradient inside (like a snow globe)
    - Gradient: #6B21A820 and #B8860B15 colors slowly rotate
    - Rotation: 8000ms per revolution, Curves.linear
  - Shadow: 0 4px 16px rgba(26,5,51,0.10) (gives the orb depth on light bg)
  - When AI is "thinking": inner gradient speeds up to 2000ms/revolution
    + shimmer highlight sweeps across surface
  - When AI delivers insight: orb briefly flashes gold
    (fill transitions to rgba(184,134,11,0.12) for 300ms then back)
  - Size: 48px diameter in-line, 120px diameter on AI detail screen

Implementation: Rive state machine with states:
  - Idle (slow swirl)
  - Listening (medium swirl + gentle scale pulse)
  - Thinking (fast swirl + shimmer)
  - Speaking (gold pulse + size pulse)
  - Dismissed (fade to 0 + scale to 0.8)

Key principle: On light mode, the orb communicates through OPACITY SHIFTS
and MOTION SPEED, not through LIGHT EMISSION. It's a contained, subtle
effect -- like peering into frosted glass, not looking at a light source.

Reference implementations:
  - react-ai-orb: A customizable animated orb for React AI interfaces,
    combining a glowing sphere rendered in fragment shader with real-time
    audio analysis influencing movement and brightness
  - ElevenLabs Orb: 3D animated orb with audio reactivity, custom colors,
    and agent state visualization built with Three.js. Colors intensify
    when listening, swirl rhythmically while thinking, pulse when speaking.
  - Elements Orb: Dynamic ball with rainbow hues responding to states

Sources:
- Material Design Snackbars: https://m1.material.io/components/snackbars-toasts.html
- Mobbin Toast UI Design: https://mobbin.com/glossary/toast
- LogRocket Toast Notifications: https://blog.logrocket.com/ux-design/toast-notifications/
- react-ai-orb Component: https://github.com/Steve0929/react-ai-orb
- ElevenLabs Orb Component: https://ui.elevenlabs.io/docs/components/orb
- Orb Animated AI Visuals: https://elements.surge.studio/ai/orb
- Flutter Toast Packages: https://fluttergems.dev/notification-toast/


================================================================================
SECTION 10: SEASONAL & SPECIAL EVENT ANIMATIONS (LIGHT MODE)
================================================================================

10.1 SNOWFALL (WINTER/CHRISTMAS)
----------------------------------

The #1 mistake: white snowflakes on #F8F5FF = invisible.

UNJYNX SOLUTION:
  - Snowflake color: #C8C0D0 (cool lavender-gray, 15% darker than bg)
  - Size range: 3-8px
  - Particle count: 20-30 (NOT 50+ like dark mode)
  - Opacity: 0.25-0.45 (lower than dark mode's 0.4-0.7)
  - Fall speed: 30-60px/second (gentle, not distracting)
  - Drift: +-15px horizontal (subtle, wind-like)
  - Rotation: slow axial rotation 3-6 seconds per revolution
  - Depth layers: 2 layers (near: larger/faster, far: smaller/slower)
  - Active period: December 15 - January 5
  - User toggle: Settings > Themes > Seasonal Effects (default ON)

Why #C8C0D0 and not pure gray:
  - Gray (#CCCCCC) on purple-tinted bg looks cold and disconnected
  - Lavender-gray harmonizes with the #F8F5FF Purple Mist background
  - Still provides enough contrast to be visible (contrast ratio ~1.3:1)

Implementation: Can use Lottie overlay in a FrameLayout/Stack approach,
adding the snowfall as a child view over the base UI. Alternatively, use
CustomPainter for full control over particle color and behavior.

10.2 DIWALI (OCTOBER/NOVEMBER)
---------------------------------

Warm colors naturally work well on light backgrounds:

  - Diya flame particles: #D4763B, #B8860B, #FFC107 (warm gradient)
  - Rangoli accent: subtle mandala pattern at 4% opacity as bg overlay
  - Sparkle particles: #B8860B at 30% opacity, 15-20 particles
  - These warm tones have NATURAL contrast against cool #F8F5FF
  - Active period: 5 days around Diwali
  - Extra: gold-tinted progress rings during the festival

10.3 HALLOWEEN (OCTOBER)
--------------------------

  - Purple fog overlay: rgba(107,33,168,0.06) -- barely perceptible
  - Bat silhouettes: #1A053315 (15% opacity midnight purple), 3-5 instances
  - Pumpkin accents: #D4763B icons replacing standard icons temporarily
  - Spider web: subtle #1A053308 (8% opacity) corner decorations
  - Active period: October 25 - November 1
  - On light mode, Halloween is SUBTLER than dark mode (where fog can be dramatic)

10.4 CHERRY BLOSSOM / SPRING (MARCH/APRIL)
---------------------------------------------

  - Petal color: #D4547A (deep rose -- NOT pastel pink which vanishes)
  - Secondary: #C2185B (even deeper, for variety)
  - Petal count: 15-25
  - Petal size: 6-12px (slightly larger to compensate for lower opacity)
  - Opacity: 0.20-0.40
  - Movement: gentle falling + rotating + slight horizontal drift
  - Active period: March 15 - April 15

10.5 AUTUMN (SEPTEMBER/OCTOBER)
---------------------------------

  - Leaf colors: #8B5E3C (brown), #B8860B (gold), #D4763B (burnt orange)
  - These warm, saturated colors have excellent visibility on #F8F5FF
  - Leaf count: 10-15 (very sparse -- ambient, not a leaf blower)
  - Size: 10-18px
  - Movement: slow falling + tumbling rotation
  - Active period: September 15 - October 24 (stops before Halloween)

10.6 LATE NIGHT AUTO-DIM
--------------------------

After 10 PM, if user is still in light mode:

  DO NOT: auto-switch to dark mode (respect user's theme choice)
  DO: Apply a subtle warm filter:
    - Background: #F8F5FF -> #F5F0ED (slightly warmer, less blue)
    - Text contrast: unchanged (maintain readability)
    - Blue light filter: reduce blue channel by 10%
    - Transition: gradual over 15 minutes (barely noticeable)

  This matches the "Night Shift" / "True Tone" philosophy:
  warmer, lower-contrast, but NOT a different theme.

10.7 CELEBRATION ENGINE (GENERIC)
-----------------------------------

A reusable celebration system for ANY achievement:

Parameters:
  - intensity: low (subtask), medium (task), high (project), epic (streak milestone)
  - colors: defaults to brand palette [#B8860B, #6B21A8, #1A0533]
  - particleCount: scales with intensity (10, 30, 50, 80)
  - duration: scales with intensity (400ms, 800ms, 1200ms, 2000ms)
  - haptic: scales (light, light, medium, heavy + success)

All particles use deep, saturated colors on light mode.
All effects use wash/shadow emphasis instead of glow.

CSS confetti animations are hardware-accelerated and run on the GPU, consume
less battery on mobile devices. The key to successful confetti animations lies
in balancing visual impact with performance, ensuring accessibility, and
maintaining subtlety that enhances rather than distracts from UX.

10.8 SEASONAL EFFECT ARCHITECTURE
-----------------------------------

  - All seasonal effects are OPTIONAL (user toggle in settings)
  - Effects render in a separate layer ABOVE content but BELOW interactions
  - Performance budget: seasonal particles max 30, max 2ms paint time
  - Disable entirely when battery saver is active
  - Disable when reduced motion accessibility setting is ON
  - Each season has a JSON config: { colors, particleCount, opacity, speed, dates }
  - Config is remotely updatable (add new seasons without app update)

Sources:
- LottieFiles Snow Animation: https://lottiefiles.com/blog/working-with-lottie-animations/add-snow-to-android-app
- Seasonly Shopify Effects: https://apps.shopify.com/snowfall
- Dakaas Seasonal Animation: https://apps.shopify.com/multi-seasonal-effects
- tsParticles Confetti: https://confetti.js.org/
- LottieFiles Confetti: https://lottiefiles.com/free-animations/confetti


================================================================================
SECTION 11: RIVE VS LOTTIE FOR LIGHT MODE
================================================================================

11.1 WHEN TO USE RIVE (INTERACTIVE, STATE-DRIVEN)
---------------------------------------------------

Rive is the PREFERRED choice when:

1. ANIMATION REACTS TO USER INPUT:
   - Checkbox: State machine with Unchecked -> Checking -> Checked states
   - Progress ring: State machine driven by percentage input (data binding)
   - Streak flame: State machine with streak count input affecting size/intensity
   - AI Whisper orb: States for Idle, Listening, Thinking, Speaking
   - Pull-to-refresh logo: Rotation speed linked to pull distance

   State Machines in Rive are a visual way to connect animations together
   and define the logic that drives transitions. A "state" is usually a
   timeline animation (like "Idle" or "Pressed"), wired together with
   transitions and connected to logic using Data Binding.

2. MULTIPLE STATES WITH TRANSITIONS:
   - Ghost Mode button: Normal -> Activating -> Active states
   - Navigation icons: Idle -> Selected with morphing animation
   - Onboarding character: Multiple emotional states

   Rive's reactive state machine listens to inputs (button presses, gestures,
   audio levels), transitions between animation states based on conditions,
   and enables fluid, logic-driven motion without hardcoding animation rules.

3. PERFORMANCE IS CRITICAL:
   - Rive files are 10-15x smaller than Lottie equivalents
   - Example: A checkbox animation in Lottie: ~240KB, in Rive: ~16KB
   - Rive's unified C++ runtime ensures consistent behavior across iOS,
     Android, Web, and Flutter
   - For animations present on EVERY task item (checkbox), Rive wins

4. LIGHT MODE COLOR REMAPPING:
   - Rive supports runtime color changes via state machine inputs
   - Color inputs can be bound to theme data (light vs dark palette)
   - No need to maintain two separate animation files

   At Slice (January 2026), they discovered Rive gave flexibility to go
   beyond static animations and build interfaces that respond directly to
   user input. Interactive components are stateful UI components that
   improve onboarding, reduce cognitive load, and create emotional
   engagement without sacrificing performance.

UNJYNX Rive animations:
  - Checkbox (complete/uncomplete): State machine with gold fill, checkmark draw
  - Progress rings (daily, project): Data-bound percentage, color transitions
  - Streak flame: Responsive to streak count, gentle idle sway
  - Ghost Mode transition: Complex multi-state entry/exit
  - AI Whisper orb: 4-state machine with motion speed modulation
  - Nav bar icons: Selected/unselected morphing

11.2 WHEN TO USE LOTTIE (FIRE-AND-FORGET)
--------------------------------------------

Lottie is the PREFERRED choice when:

1. ONE-TIME PLAYBACK:
   - Confetti celebration: plays once, then disposes
   - Empty state illustrations: simple idle loop, no interaction
   - Onboarding page animations: sequential playback
   - Achievement unlock fanfare: single dramatic play

2. DESIGNER WORKFLOW:
   - Designers export from After Effects -> Lottie (established pipeline)
   - Complex illustrations with many layers (easier in AE than Rive editor)
   - Pre-made animations from LottieFiles marketplace (vast library)

3. LIGHT MODE COLOR ADAPTATION:
   - Modify Lottie JSON at runtime in Flutter (Dart JSON parsing)
   - Replace color values in the JSON before passing to LottieComposition
   - This allows one animation file to work for both themes

   Approach in Flutter:
   a. Load Lottie JSON as string
   b. Parse and replace color hex values:
      Dark mode gold #FFD700 -> Light mode deep gold #B8860B
      Dark mode glow #FFFFFF -> Light mode shadow #1A053340
   c. Create LottieComposition from modified JSON
   d. Cache the modified composition for reuse

   Rather than exporting multiple versions from After Effects, you can edit
   the raw JSON on the fly in Flutter using Dart to create personalized
   animations and show real-time feedback.

4. COMPLEXITY IS HIGH BUT INTERACTION IS LOW:
   - Highly detailed illustrations (characters, scenes)
   - Particle effects that Rive's editor can't easily replicate
   - Gradient-heavy animations

UNJYNX Lottie animations:
  - Confetti celebrations (all tiers)
  - Empty state illustrations (empty inbox, all done, no results)
  - Onboarding tutorial screens (3-5 animated pages)
  - Achievement unlock effects
  - Seasonal overlays (snowfall, sakura -- could also be CustomPainter)

11.3 LATE 2025 MARKET SHIFT
------------------------------

In late 2025, LottieFiles introduced a native State Machine in a web-based
Lottie Creator with generative AI capabilities, eliminating the historical
distinction that "Lottie = linear, Rive = stateful."

The new competition is between:
  - Lottie: AI-accelerated, open ecosystem-driven velocity
  - Rive: Mature, high-performance, technically-focused control

For UNJYNX, Rive remains preferred for hot-path interactive animations
due to the C++ runtime performance advantage and smaller file sizes.
Lottie is preferred for the marketplace ecosystem and designer workflow.

11.4 COST AND SIZE COMPARISON
-------------------------------

                        | RIVE              | LOTTIE
------------------------|-------------------|------------------
File size (checkbox)    | ~3KB              | ~45KB
File size (character)   | ~16KB             | ~240KB
Runtime (Flutter)       | C++ native        | Dart + Skia
State machine           | Built-in, visual  | New (late 2025)
Color remapping         | Input-driven      | JSON modification
Interactive             | Native support    | Limited (improving)
Designer learning curve | Moderate (new UI) | Low (After Effects)
Cost                    | Free tier + paid  | Free + marketplace
Community               | Growing (2026)    | Large, established

11.5 HYBRID STRATEGY FOR UNJYNX
----------------------------------

CRITICAL PATH (user sees every session): RIVE
  - Checkbox, progress rings, nav icons, streak flame

CELEBRATION/DELIGHT (occasional): LOTTIE
  - Confetti, empty states, achievements, onboarding

BACKGROUND EFFECTS: CUSTOMPAINTER
  - Particles, seasonal effects (full control, no external dependency)

This hybrid approach optimizes for:
  - Performance (Rive on hot paths)
  - Development speed (Lottie for one-off animations)
  - Flexibility (CustomPainter for brand-specific effects)

