================================================================================
SECTION 12: FLUTTER IMPLEMENTATION PATTERNS
================================================================================

12.1 ANIMATION APPROACH DECISION TREE
---------------------------------------

Is it interactive (responds to user input)?
  YES -> Is it on a hot path (every list item)?
    YES -> RIVE (smallest, fastest)
    NO  -> RIVE or Flutter AnimationController
  NO -> Is it complex (many layers, characters)?
    YES -> LOTTIE (designer-friendly export)
    NO  -> Is it a simple property change?
      YES -> IMPLICIT ANIMATION (AnimatedContainer, AnimatedOpacity, etc.)
      NO  -> EXPLICIT ANIMATION (AnimationController + Tween)

12.2 IMPLICIT ANIMATIONS (SIMPLEST)
--------------------------------------

Implicit animations are prebuilt animation effects that run the entire
animation automatically. When the target value changes, the animation runs
from the current value to the target value, displaying each value in between
so the widget animates smoothly.

Use for single-property changes that respond to state:

AnimatedContainer:
  - Card elevation changes on selection
  - Background color changes on hover/press
  - Size changes on expand/collapse
  - Duration: 200-300ms, Curve: Curves.easeOutCubic

AnimatedOpacity:
  - Text fading on completion (1.0 -> 0.5)
  - Element appearing/disappearing
  - Duration: 200ms, Curve: Curves.easeInOut

AnimatedScale:
  - Button press feedback (1.0 -> 0.97)
  - Badge entrance (0.0 -> 1.0)
  - Duration: 150ms, Curve: Curves.easeOutBack

AnimatedSwitcher:
  - Tab content crossfade
  - Number display changes
  - Icon state changes
  - Duration: 150ms with FadeTransition

Light mode note: These implicit animations work identically on light and dark.
The difference is in the COLOR VALUES, not the animation behavior.

12.3 EXPLICIT ANIMATIONS (COMPLEX SEQUENCES)
----------------------------------------------

Use for multi-phase, choreographed animations. A staggered animation consists
of sequential or overlapping animations -- one AnimationController controls
all of the Animations, and each Animation object specifies the animation
during an Interval.

CHECKBOX COMPLETION (example):
  // AnimationController setup
  final controller = AnimationController(
    duration: const Duration(milliseconds: 550),
    vsync: this,
  );

  // Phase animations using Interval
  final fillAnimation = ColorTween(
    begin: Colors.transparent,
    end: const Color(0xFFB8860B), // Rich gold
  ).animate(CurvedAnimation(
    parent: controller,
    curve: const Interval(0.09, 0.45, curve: Curves.easeOutBack),
  ));

  final strikethroughAnimation = Tween<double>(
    begin: 0.0,
    end: 1.0,
  ).animate(CurvedAnimation(
    parent: controller,
    curve: const Interval(0.45, 0.82, curve: Curves.easeInOut),
  ));

  final washAnimation = Tween<double>(
    begin: 0.0,
    end: 80.0, // wash radius in pixels
  ).animate(CurvedAnimation(
    parent: controller,
    curve: const Interval(0.36, 0.73, curve: Curves.easeOut),
  ));

12.4 FLUTTER_ANIMATE PACKAGE
------------------------------

The flutter_animate package simplifies chained animations:

  Widget buildTaskItem() {
    return taskCard
      .animate(onPlay: (c) => c.forward())
      .fadeIn(duration: 300.ms, curve: Curves.easeOut)
      .slideX(begin: 0.05, end: 0, duration: 300.ms)
      .then() // chain after previous completes
      .shimmer(
        duration: 600.ms,
        color: const Color(0x0CB8860B), // subtle gold shimmer
      );
  }

For staggered lists:
  ListView.builder(
    itemBuilder: (context, index) {
      return listItem
        .animate(delay: (50 * index).ms) // 50ms stagger
        .fadeIn(duration: 300.ms)
        .slideX(begin: 0.02, end: 0);
    },
  )

12.5 HERO TRANSITIONS
-----------------------

For task card -> detail screen:

  // Source screen (list)
  Hero(
    tag: 'task-${task.id}',
    child: Material(
      elevation: 1,
      shadowColor: const Color(0x201A0533), // light purple shadow
      borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(12),
      child: TaskCardWidget(task: task),
    ),
  )

  // Destination screen (detail)
  Hero(
    tag: 'task-${task.id}',
    flightShuttleBuilder: (flightContext, animation, direction,
        fromContext, toContext) {
      return Material(
        elevation: animation.value * 8, // shadow increases during flight
        shadowColor: const Color(0x301A0533),
        borderRadius: BorderRadius.circular(12),
        child: toContext.widget,
      );
    },
    child: TaskDetailWidget(task: task),
  )

12.6 SHIMMER CONFIGURATION FOR LIGHT MODE
-------------------------------------------

Using the shimmer package (pub.dev/packages/shimmer):

  Shimmer.fromColors(
    baseColor: const Color(0xFFF0EAF5),     // Lavender base
    highlightColor: const Color(0xFFF8F5FF), // Purple Mist highlight
    period: const Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
    child: skeletonLayout,
  )

Using Skeletonizer:
  Skeletonizer(
    effect: ShimmerEffect(
      baseColor: const Color(0xFFF0EAF5),
      highlightColor: const Color(0xFFF8F5FF),
      duration: const Duration(milliseconds: 1500),
    ),
    child: actualLayout, // Skeletonizer auto-converts to skeleton
  )

12.7 CUSTOM PAINTER FOR PARTICLES
------------------------------------

  class LightModeParticlePainter extends CustomPainter {
    final List<Particle> particles;
    final double progress;

    LightModeParticlePainter({
      required this.particles,
      required this.progress,
    });

    @override
    void paint(Canvas canvas, Size size) {
      final paint = Paint()
        ..blendMode = BlendMode.srcOver // NOT BlendMode.plus (additive)
        ..maskFilter = const MaskFilter.blur(BlurStyle.normal, 1.0);

      for (final particle in particles) {
        paint.color = particle.color.withOpacity(
          particle.baseOpacity * (1.0 - progress), // fade over lifetime
        );
        canvas.drawCircle(
          particle.position,
          particle.radius,
          paint,
        );
      }
    }

    @override
    bool shouldRepaint(LightModeParticlePainter oldDelegate) {
      return oldDelegate.progress != progress;
    }
  }

Key light-mode specifics in this painter:
  - BlendMode.srcOver (standard alpha compositing, NOT additive)
  - MaskFilter.blur at 1.0 (soft edges, not sharp -- less harsh on light)
  - Opacity always below 0.35 for ambient particles

12.8 STAGGERED LIST ANIMATION
-------------------------------

Using flutter_staggered_animations:

  AnimationLimiter(
    child: ListView.builder(
      itemCount: tasks.length,
      itemBuilder: (context, index) {
        return AnimationConfiguration.staggeredList(
          position: index,
          duration: const Duration(milliseconds: 300),
          child: SlideAnimation(
            horizontalOffset: 20.0, // subtle horizontal slide
            child: FadeInAnimation(
              child: TaskListItem(task: tasks[index]),
            ),
          ),
        );
      },
    ),
  )

Note: Limit animation to first 10 items. Beyond that, items appear instantly.
This prevents long lists from having awkward delayed appearance.

12.9 PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATION CHECKLIST
-----------------------------------------

For light mode (same principles, different visuals):

  [ ] Use RepaintBoundary around animated widgets (isolate repaint regions)
  [ ] Avoid Opacity widget for fading (use FadeTransition or AnimatedOpacity)
  [ ] Minimize saveLayer() calls (expensive compositing)
  [ ] Pre-calculate particle positions (avoid per-frame allocation)
  [ ] Use const constructors for static paint configurations
  [ ] Profile with Flutter DevTools: aim for <8ms per frame on animations
  [ ] Test on low-end devices (mid-range Android is the floor)
  [ ] Respect MediaQuery.disableAnimations for accessibility
  [ ] Cache Rive/Lottie compositions (don't reload per build)
  [ ] Use Ticker/vsync properly (dispose controllers in dispose())

Sources:
- Flutter Animation Introduction: https://docs.flutter.dev/ui/animations
- Flutter Implicit Animations Codelab: https://docs.flutter.dev/codelabs/implicit-animations
- Flutter Staggered Menu Animation: https://docs.flutter.dev/cookbook/effects/staggered-menu-animation
- flutter_staggered_animations: https://pub.dev/documentation/flutter_staggered_animations/latest/
- Lottie Flutter Package: https://pub.dev/packages/lottie
- Skeletonizer Package: https://pub.dev/packages/skeletonizer
- Flexiple Advanced Flutter Animations: https://flexiple.com/app/advanced-flutter-animations
- Very Good Ventures CustomPainter: https://www.verygood.ventures/blog/mastering-custompainter-in-flutter-from-svgs-to-racetracks
- Codecademy Flutter Animations Tutorial: https://www.codecademy.com/article/how-to-create-flutter-animation
- Flutter Gems Animation Packages: https://fluttergems.dev/animation-transition/


================================================================================
SECTION 13: ACCESSIBILITY & REDUCED MOTION
================================================================================

13.1 REDUCED MOTION COMPLIANCE
---------------------------------

UNJYNX MUST respect the platform's "Reduce Motion" setting. Vestibular
disorders affect more than 70 million people worldwide, and motion sensitivity
affects approximately 35% of adults over 40. These conditions can cause loss
of balance, vertigo, migraines, nausea, and hearing loss when exposed to
excessive screen motion.

Detection in Flutter:
  final reduceMotion = MediaQuery.of(context).disableAnimations;
  // Also check: WidgetsBinding.instance.disableAnimations

Platform settings locations:
  - Windows 10: Settings > Ease of Access > Display > Show animations
  - Windows 11: Settings > Accessibility > Visual Effects > Animation Effects
  - macOS: System Settings > Accessibility > Display > Reduce motion
  - iOS: Settings > Accessibility > Motion
  - Android 9+: Settings > Accessibility > Remove animations

When reduced motion is ON:
  - ALL decorative animations: DISABLED (particles, celebrations, seasonal)
  - Transition animations: replaced with INSTANT CUT or simple FADE (200ms)
  - Completion animations: checkbox fills instantly (no draw animation)
  - Progress rings: jump to target value (no sweep animation)
  - Shimmer loading: replaced with static skeleton (no shimmer sweep)
  - Parallax: disabled (1:1 scroll ratio)
  - Page transitions: crossfade only, no slides
  - Staggered lists: all items appear simultaneously

When reduced motion is ON, KEEP:
  - Color transitions (they're not motion, they're state feedback)
  - Opacity changes (subtle, not motion-triggering)
  - Essential feedback (error shake can be replaced with color flash)

IMPORTANT: "Reduced motion" is NOT "no motion" -- provide alternatives.
Most animations, especially decorative effects such as fades, slides, parallax,
or hover transitions can simply be removed. But users still expect motion
animation triggered by user interaction unless the animation is essential to
the functionality or information being conveyed.

13.2 ANIMATION DURATION ACCESSIBILITY
---------------------------------------

Even with reduced motion OFF, UNJYNX provides user control:

Settings > Accessibility > Animation Speed:
  - Full (default): all durations as specified
  - Reduced: all durations * 0.5 (faster, less noticeable)
  - Minimal: all durations * 0.25 (barely perceptible)
  - None: equivalent to system reduced motion

This is implemented via a global animation speed multiplier:

  // In animation_config.dart
  double getAnimationDuration(double baseDurationMs) {
    final multiplier = ref.read(animationSpeedProvider);
    return baseDurationMs * multiplier;
  }

Even with prefers-reduced-motion techniques, you still need to add a pause
option for movement or animation that lasts more than five seconds. That way
users who don't have the setting on still have the option to stop the animation.

13.3 VESTIBULAR DISORDER CONSIDERATIONS
-----------------------------------------

Key UNJYNX mitigations:

  - Parallax speed capped at 0.3x (never > 0.5x)
  - No auto-playing full-screen animations
  - No zoom/scale transitions that fill the viewport
  - Particle motion is ALWAYS gentle and slow
  - Ghost Mode circular reveal can be replaced with crossfade
  - All looping animations stop after 5 seconds max (per WCAG 2.2.2)
    OR provide visible pause control

13.4 COLOR CONTRAST ON ANIMATIONS
------------------------------------

Light mode has specific contrast challenges for animated elements:

  - Shimmer must have base/highlight contrast of at least 1.2:1
    Our #F0EAF5 / #F8F5FF = 1.04:1 (intentionally subtle, decorative only)
  - Progress ring fill must contrast with track:
    #6B21A8 on #EDE5F7 = 5.1:1 (excellent)
  - Toast text must meet 4.5:1:
    #FFFFFF on #1A0533 = 15.8:1 (excellent)
  - Disabled elements at 40% opacity:
    #1A0533 at 40% on #F8F5FF = ~4.2:1 (meets WCAG AA)
  - Focus ring on background:
    #6B21A8 on #F8F5FF = 7.2:1 (exceeds WCAG AAA)

13.5 REGULATORY COMPLIANCE
-----------------------------

  - WCAG 2.1 AA: Required (all animations must have alternatives)
  - WCAG 2.2.2: Auto-playing animation must pause after 5 seconds
  - European Accessibility Act 2025: New UK and EU laws tightening
    accessibility rules, with specific animation guidelines. All digital
    services must meet tougher standards by 2025.
  - India DPDP Act: Accessibility provisions in development
  - IMPORTANT: "Reduced motion" is NOT "no motion" -- provide alternatives

